    "lesson_id": "002",
    "trigger_word": "estas",
    "title": "LESSON 2: PRESENT TENSE",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "In Esperanto, present tense is simple:",
          "ALL verbs end in -as, no matter who is",
          "doing the action.",
          "",
          "EXAMPLES WITH 'ESTI' (to be):",
          "",
          "mi estas      = I am",
          "vi estas      = you are",
          "li estas      = he is",
          "ŝi estas      = she is",
          "ni estas      = we are",
          "ili estas     = they are",
          "",
          "EXAMPLES WITH 'PAROLI' (to speak):",
          "mi parolas    = I speak",
          "vi parolas    = you speak",
          "li parolas    = he speaks",
          "",
          "The verb NEVER changes! One form for all."
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono du"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "003",
    "trigger_word": "alia",
    "title": "LESSON 3: ADJECTIVES & PLURALS",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 2,
        "content": [
          "Every adjective in Esperanto ends in -a.",
          "This makes them easy to spot!",
          "",
          "COMMON ADJECTIVES:",
          "",
          "bona   = good        malbona   = bad",
          "granda = big         malgranda = small",
          "bela   = beautiful   nova      = new",
          "",
          "WORD ORDER - Both ways work:",
          "",
          "bona libro  = a good book",
          "libro bona  = a good book (also OK!)",
          "",
          "TIP: If it describes a noun and ends in",
          "-a, it's an adjective. Simple!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono tri"
      },
      {
        "page": 2,
        "total_pages": 2,
        "content": [
          "PLURALS: Add -j to nouns AND adjectives.",
          "",
          "NOUNS (-o becomes -oj):",
          "",
          "amiko   → amikoj    = friend → friends",
          "libro   → libroj    = book → books",
          "hundo   → hundoj    = dog → dogs",
          "",
          "ADJECTIVES MUST MATCH:",
          "bona amiko    → bonaj amikoj",
          "granda libro  → grandaj libroj",
          "",
          "PRONUNCIATION:",
          "The -j sounds like 'y' in 'boy'.",
          "amikoj = ah-MEE-koy",
          "",
          "Both noun AND adjective get -j!",
          "La grandaj hundoj kuras. = The big dogs run."
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "004",
    "trigger_word": "bone",
    "title": "LESSON 4: ADVERBS END IN -E",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "Adverbs describe HOW something happens.",
          "In Esperanto, they always end in -e.",
          "",
          "FROM ADJECTIVE TO ADVERB:",
          "bona → bone       = good → well",
          "rapida → rapide   = quick → quickly",
          "facila → facile   = easy → easily",
          "lenta → lente     = slow → slowly",
          "",
          "THE DIFFERENCE:",
          "",
          "Li estas bona.",
          "(He is good. ← describes HIM)",
          "",
          "Li kantas bone.",
          "(He sings well. ← describes HOW)",
          "",
          "Remember: -a for nouns, -e for actions!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono kvar"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "005",
    "trigger_word": "kio",
    "title": "LESSON 5: QUESTION WORDS (KI-)",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "All question words in Esperanto start",
          "with KI-. This is part of a beautiful",
          "system you'll learn more about later!",
          "",
          "THE QUESTION WORDS:",
          "kio   = what (thing)",
          "kiu   = who / which one",
          "kie   = where (place)",
          "kiam  = when (time)",
          "kial  = why (reason)",
          "kiel  = how (manner)",
          "kiom  = how much / how many",
          "",
          "EXAMPLES:",
          "Kio estas tio?     = What is that?",
          "Kiu vi estas?      = Who are you?",
          "Kie vi loĝas?      = Where do you live?",
          "Kiam vi venas?     = When are you coming?"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono kvin"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "006",
    "trigger_word": "helpo",
    "title": "LESSON 6: THE ARTICLE \"LA\"",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "Esperanto has ONE article: LA (the).",
          "",
          "WITH LA = specific, known thing:",
          "Mi vidas la hundon. = I see the dog.",
          "La libro relevanta estas sur la tablo.",
          "= The relevant book is on the table.",
          "",
          "WITHOUT ARTICLE = general concept:",
          "Mi amas muzikon. = I love music.",
          "Akvo estas necesa. = Water is necessary.",
          "Ŝi volas kafon. = She wants coffee.",
          "",
          "COMPARE:",
          "Mi legas libron. = I'm reading a book.",
          "Mi legas la libron. = I'm reading the book.",
          "",
          "No a/an in Esperanto - context tells you!",
          "LA never changes: la viro, la viroj, la domo."
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono ses"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "007",
    "trigger_word": "ĉu",
    "title": "LESSON 7: YES/NO QUESTIONS",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "To turn any statement into a yes/no",
          "question, just add ĈU at the beginning.",
          "The word order stays exactly the same!",
          "",
          "STATEMENT → QUESTION:",
          "Vi parolas Esperanton.",
          "(You speak Esperanto.)",
          "  ↓",
          "Ĉu vi parolas Esperanton?",
          "(Do you speak Esperanto?)",
          "",
          "MORE EXAMPLES:",
          "Ĉu estas problemo?  = Is there a problem?",
          "Ĉu li venas?        = Is he coming?",
          "Ĉu vi komprenas?    = Do you understand?",
          "",
          "ANSWERS: Jes = Yes  /  Ne = No"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono sep"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "008",
    "trigger_word": "patrino",
    "title": "LESSON 8: FEMININE SUFFIX -IN-",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "To make a word specifically female, add",
          "-IN- after the root, before the ending.",
          "",
          "FAMILY MEMBERS:",
          "patro → patrino    = father → mother",
          "frato → fratino    = brother → sister",
          "filo → filino      = son → daughter",
          "",
          "STRUCTURE:",
          "patr-in-o  = mother (noun -o)",
          "patr-in-a  = motherly (adjective -a)",
          "",
          "WORKS WITH ANYTHING:",
          "knabo → knabino    = boy → girl",
          "hundo → hundino    = dog → female dog",
          "amiko → amikino    = friend → girlfriend"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono ok"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "009",
